Further Exploration¶

In this notebook, we perform two types of analysis to deepen our understanding of the Endomondo workout dataset:

  1. Descriptive Analysis: We explore workout metrics through visualizations and statistics to uncover patterns and trends.
  2. Predictive Analysis: We develop a classification model to categorize workouts into intensity levels (e.g., low, moderate, high), showcasing a potential use case for workout recommendations.

In the subsequent sections, we will define the specific problems, set objectives, and outline the approach for each type of analysis.

1 Descriptive Analysis¶

Problem Definition¶

In this analysis, we will group the workout data based on sport type to explore various metrics and uncover trends that may offer valuable insights. Our primary focus will be on the following metrics:

  • Unique Sessions: Determining the total number of workout entries logged for each sport to gauge popularity.
  • Average Heart Rate: Calculating the mean heart rate across different sports to understand the intensity associated with each type of workout.

Grouping Sports for Analysis

Based on prior observations from Assignment 1, over 99% of the data consists of biking and running activities. To improve the readability of our visualizations, we will categorize sports into three groups: bike, run, and others. These categories are defined as follows:

  • Bike: Includes 'bike', 'bike (transport)', 'mountain bike', and 'indoor cycling'.
  • Run: Directly mapped to the 'run' category in the dataset.
  • Others: Comprises all remaining sports types in the dataset.

Then, we will examine:

  • Day of the Week: Analyzing the distribution of workouts across weekdays and weekends to identify potential trends in workout frequency.
  • Start Time: Investigating the typical start times for workouts to understand user behavior and preferences for different times of day.
  • Workout Length: Assessing the duration of workouts to highlight patterns or trends in how long users typically engage in each sport.

Visualizations will support this analysis, helping us identify any patterns or trends that warrant further exploration.

Note: The dataset lacks timezone information, so we will assume that all timestamps are in a single, consistent timezone.

Let's start by calculating the average heart rate and the number of unique sessions for each sport category. This will give us an overview of workout intensity and the distribution of sessions across different activities.

Workout Patterns by Day and Time¶

In this section, we analyze workout patterns across different days of the week and times of the day. By examining when users engage in various activities, we can uncover trends in their workout habits, such as preferred workout days, start times, and session durations.

This analysis is based on the following metrics:

  • Day of the Week: We identify which days are the most popular for workouts across different sports categories.
  • Starting Hour: By analyzing workout start times, we explore if users prefer morning, afternoon, or evening sessions.
  • Workout Duration: We calculate the total duration of each workout session, helping us understand typical workout lengths across different days and times.

To do this, we prepared the dataset by:

  • For each workout session, we identified the start and end times and calculated the duration (in minutes) based on these.
  • We also extracted the day of the week and starting hour from the timestamp to explore weekly trends and preferred workout times.
In [8]:
# Create a copy with relevant columns
day_and_time_data = endomondo_df[['timestamp', 'id', 'sport']].copy()

# Add a new column 'sport_category' using the sport_mapping
day_and_time_data['sport_category'] = day_and_time_data['sport'].map(sport_mapping).fillna('others')

# Ensure timestamp is in datetime format (if not already)
day_and_time_data['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(day_and_time_data['timestamp'])

# Extract date and calculate start and end times in a single operation
day_and_time_data['date'] = day_and_time_data['timestamp'].dt.date
day_and_time_data['day_of_week'] = day_and_time_data['timestamp'].dt.day_name()
day_and_time_data['starting_hour'] = day_and_time_data['timestamp'].dt.hour

# Group by id, sport_category, and date to calculate start, end, and duration
day_and_time_summary = day_and_time_data.groupby(['id', 'sport_category', 'date']).agg(
    start_time=('timestamp', 'min'),
    end_time=('timestamp', 'max')
).reset_index()

# Calculate duration in minutes
day_and_time_summary['duration'] = (day_and_time_summary['end_time'] - day_and_time_summary['start_time']).dt.total_seconds() / 60

# Add day of the week and starting hour columns for easier analysis
day_and_time_summary['day_of_week'] = day_and_time_summary['start_time'].dt.day_name()
day_and_time_summary['starting_hour'] = day_and_time_summary['start_time'].dt.hour

# Display the resulting DataFrame
day_and_time_summary.head()

The visualization uses a stacked bar chart, where:

  • Each bar represents a day of the week, displaying the total workout sessions for that day.

Observations¶

Average Heart Rate per Sport:

  • Expectedly, Walking has the lowest Average Heart Rate, with Hiking as the second lowest
  • Skating quite clearly has the highest Average Heart Rate, which is unexpected, given that there are arguably more intensive sports like running in the dataset

Unique Session per Sport:

  • From the bar chart, we can clearly see that Bike and Run are overwhelmingly the most popular sports based on our data
  • Also the next few (distant) popular sports are all also bike-related: Bike (Transport), Mountain Bike, and Indoor Cycling

Workouts per Day of Week:

  • Distribution is different from what we expected. One would expect that there would be a significantly larger amounts of workout performed during the weekends but this does not appear to be the case
  • Workouts seem to be fairly evenly distributed across the week, with notably lower number of workouts performed on Mondays and Fridays. Workouts on the other days in the week seems fairly equal though.

Workouts per Hour of Day:

  • There is a surprisingly high number of workouts recorded between 12:00 AM and 1:00 AM, which is significantly higher than expected, almost twice compared to any other 1-hour intervals during the day.
  • That said, most of the workouts occur between 1600H and 2359H, which is within expectations

Timezone Assumption: These patterns may be influenced by the absence of timezone information in the dataset. All timestamps are recorded in the same, unknown timezone, which may skew the distribution of workouts across different times of day and days of the week. For instance, the large number of midnight workouts might actually correspond to workouts conducted in the late evening or early morning in a different timezone.

Distribution of Workouts by Duration:

  • Most workout durations lie between 30 mins and 80 mins, which is within expectations.

2 Predictive Analysis¶

Problem Definition¶

In this section, we explore whether workout intensity can be classified based on various workout features, specifically:

  • Speed
  • Heart Rate
  • Elevation (Altitude)

By predicting the intensity of workouts, users can gain insights into how strenuous their workouts are and make informed adjustments as needed. The classification of workout intensity into categories such as High, Medium, and Low provides a clear metric for users to monitor and evaluate their progress.

Through this analysis, we aim to:

  • Classify workout sessions into intensity levels based on available features.
  • Predict the intensity of new workout sessions, allowing for real-time feedback and adjustments.

The insights from this predictive model can help users optimize their training efforts by ensuring they’re working out at their desired intensity levels. It also facilitates goal-setting and monitoring, making it easier to align workouts with fitness objectives.

Training a model to classify workouts by intensity¶

Ideally, with labelled data, we can use more performant supervised learning models such as KNN or random forest to perform classification. These can also be fine tuned to perform well by comparing the predicted labels and the ground truth.

However, as the dataset is unlabelled, we have to resort to unsupervised learning models to perform classification. We decided to use k-means clustering as we have a clear idea on the number of clusters we need. In our case, we want 3 clusters because we want to classify workouts into 3 categories, high intensity, medium intensity, and low intensity. Thereafter, we perform a manual review to assign each of the three clusters to an intensity level.

number_of_workout_intensity_levels = 3 # high, medium, low
random_seed_for_reproducibility = 42
number_of_samples_to_review_per_cluster = 10

pd.set_option('display.max_rows', number_of_samples_to_review_per_cluster)  # Show all rows
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)  # Show all columns
pd.set_option('display.width', 1000)  # Set width for better formatting

# Prepare data
# - need to "consolidate" data for each user for their entire workout because it does not make sense to cluster each part of a user's workout
# - max and min heart rate, as well as the total heart rate range are included because:
#     - fitter individuals tend to have lower resting heart rates and experience smaller increases in heart rate during exercise compared to less fit individuals, even when performing workouts of the same intensity
#     - therefore using the range of heart rates recorded during the workout alone would not be accurate
# - features for k-means clustering
#     - max heart rate
#     - min heart rate
#     - change in heart rate
#     - change in altitude (computed as the cumulative sum of abs(altitude_diff) for the entire workout)
#     - workout duration (same computation logic as above)
#     - distance travelled (same computation logic as above)
#     - average speed (recomputed as distance / time) (not sure if it matters but ideally should provide time-weighted average speed for best chance of good results?)

def prepare_data(
    data, # endomondo_df
    sport, # "bike" or "run"
):
    # Ensure 'timestamp' column is in datetime format
    data['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(data['timestamp'])

    # Filter data for the specified sport
    filtered_data = data[data['sport'] == sport].copy() # copy data
    results = pd.DataFrame(filtered_data['id']).drop_duplicates()

    # Calculate altitude_diff if it does not exist
    if 'altitude_diff' not in filtered_data.columns:
        filtered_data['altitude_diff'] = filtered_data.groupby('id')['altitude'].diff().fillna(0)

    # Calculate time_elapsed if it does not exist
    if 'time_elapsed' not in filtered_data.columns:
        filtered_data['time_elapsed'] = filtered_data.groupby('id')['timestamp'].diff().dt.total_seconds().fillna(0)

    # Calculate speed_diff if it does not exist
    if 'speed_diff' not in filtered_data.columns:
        filtered_data['speed_diff'] = filtered_data.groupby('id')['speed'].diff().fillna(0)

    # retrieve max heart rate
    max_heart_rates = filtered_data.groupby('id')['heart_rate'].max().reset_index(name='max_heart_rate')
    results = pd.merge(results, max_heart_rates, on='id', how='left')

    # retrieve min heart rate
    min_heart_rates = filtered_data.groupby('id')['heart_rate'].min().reset_index(name='min_heart_rate')
    results = pd.merge(results, min_heart_rates, on='id', how='left')

    # compute the total range of heart rate
    results['heart_rate_range'] = results['max_heart_rate'] - results['min_heart_rate']

    # compute the change in altitude
    filtered_data.loc[:, 'absolute_altitude_diff'] = filtered_data['altitude_diff'].abs()
    altitudes = filtered_data.groupby('id')['absolute_altitude_diff'].sum().reset_index()
    results = pd.merge(results, altitudes, on='id', how='left')

    # compute workout duration
    durations = filtered_data.groupby('id')['timestamp'].agg(
        workout_time=lambda x: (x.max() - x.min()).total_seconds()
    ).reset_index()
    results = pd.merge(results, durations, on='id', how='left')

    # compute distance travelled
    filtered_data.loc[:,'distance_travelled'] = filtered_data['time_elapsed'] * (filtered_data['speed']*1000/3600 - filtered_data['speed_diff']*1000/3600) # assuming speed is in km/h, convert to m/s
    distances = filtered_data.groupby('id')['distance_travelled'].sum().reset_index()
    results = pd.merge(results, distances, on='id', how='left')

    # compute average speed
    results['avg_speed'] = results['distance_travelled'] / results['workout_time']

    return results

bike_data_for_k_means = prepare_data(endomondo_df, 'bike')
run_data_for_k_means = prepare_data(endomondo_df, 'run')

# function to help with visualising the results
# - shape is not implemented at the moment, logic of function will need to change if we are also plotting different shapes
def visualise_clusters(sport, data, min_max_scaler, k_means_model, x_axis, y_axis, color=None, size=None):
    # Create a scatter plot of the data, with a different shape for each cluster
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    if size:
      scatter = plt.scatter(data[x_axis], data[y_axis], c=data[color], s=data[size], cmap='viridis', alpha=0.6)
    else:
      scatter = plt.scatter(data[x_axis], data[y_axis], c=data[color], cmap='viridis', alpha=0.6)

    # Add cluster centroids to the plot
    # - the centroids are normalised so we would need to reverse the normalisation before plotting them
    centroids = pd.DataFrame(min_max_scaler.inverse_transform(k_means_model.cluster_centers_), columns=data.columns[1:-1]) # reverse the normalisation before plotting, remove "id" and "cluster" columns
    plt.scatter(centroids[x_axis], centroids[y_axis], color='red', marker='x', s=100, label='Centroids')

    # Add labels and legend
    plt.title(f'{sport} workouts clustered for intensity of workout')
    plt.xlabel(x_axis)
    plt.ylabel(y_axis)
    plt.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title='Clusters')
    plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
    plt.show()

def pick_samples(data, seed, cluster_number, number_of_samples):
    return data[data["cluster"] == cluster_number].sample(n=number_of_samples, random_state=seed)

Predicting Intensity of Unseen Workout¶

In [19]:
# create fictitious bike workout details (manipulated to be of high intensity)
new_workout = pd.DataFrame({'max_heart_rate': [180],
                            'min_heart_rate': [60],
                            'heart_rate_range': [120],
                            'absolute_altitude_diff': [1000],
                            'workout_time': [10800],
                            'distance_travelled': [129600],
                            'avg_speed': [12]})

def find_closest_centroid(data_point, centroids):
  """
  Finds the closest centroid to a given data point.

  Args:
    data_point: A list or numpy array representing the data point.
    centroids: A list of lists or a numpy array representing the centroids.

  Returns:
    The index of the closest centroid.
  """
  distances = [np.linalg.norm(np.array(data_point) - np.array(centroid)) for centroid in centroids]
  return np.argmin(distances)

# Find the closest centroid to the new workout
bike_centroids = bike_k_means.cluster_centers_

new_workout_scaled = bike_min_max_scaler.transform(new_workout)

closest_centroid_index = find_closest_centroid(new_workout_scaled, bike_centroids)

# Print the closest centroid index
print(f"The closest centroid to the new workout is centroid {closest_centroid_index}.")

The closest centroid to the new workout is centroid 2.

With the closest centroid to the new workout identified, we can then map the new workout to either high, medium, or low intensity based on the mapping determined through manual review of the clustering results performed above

Conclusion¶

Through our model using k-means clustering, we are able to predict the intensity of a new unseen workout instance. Therefore, we hope that our model would e able to enable users to make informed decisions about adjusting their workout intensity, helping them stay on track to achieve their fitness goals.
